# Psychological and Cognitive Foundations of Belief in Conspiracy Theories

Belief in conspiracy theories is a widespread phenomenon that has garnered increasing attention in psychological research over the past few decades. Despite the often implausible nature of many conspiracy theories, a substantial portion of the population endorses at least one such belief, highlighting the need for a comprehensive understanding of the underlying causes. This report synthesizes findings from systematic reviews, meta-analyses, and empirical studies to provide an in-depth exploration of the psychological, cognitive, and social factors that contribute to conspiracy belief. The analysis prioritizes recent, reliable sources and integrates diverse perspectives to elucidate why people believe in conspiracies.

---

## 1. Cognitive Mechanisms Underpinning Conspiracy Beliefs

### 1.1 Illusory Pattern Perception and Need for Control

A core cognitive factor implicated in conspiracy belief is **illusory pattern perception**—the tendency to perceive meaningful patterns in random or unrelated stimuli. This cognitive bias leads individuals to connect disparate events or data points into coherent narratives, even when such connections are unfounded. Research demonstrates that individuals who believe in conspiracy theories are more likely to see patterns in random sequences, chaotic visual stimuli, and ambiguous information ([van Prooijen & Acker, 2015](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.1159845); [Bruder et al., 2013](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full)).

The motivation for such pattern perception is often linked to a **lack of control**. When people experience uncertainty or powerlessness, they have an increased psychological need to restore a sense of order and predictability. Conspiracy theories provide a compensatory mechanism by offering clear causal explanations and attributing events to intentional agents, thereby satisfying this need ([van Prooijen & Acker, 2015](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.1159845)). Experimental evidence shows that inducing feelings of lacking control increases illusory pattern perception and conspiracy beliefs, effects that can be mitigated through self-affirmation interventions ([van Prooijen & Acker, 2015](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.1159845)).

### 1.2 Cognitive Biases: Jumping-to-Conclusions and Hypersensitive Agency Detection

Believers in conspiracy theories also exhibit specific cognitive biases such as the **jumping-to-conclusions bias**, characterized by making hasty decisions based on limited evidence. This bias is notably observed in schizophrenia patients and is linked to conspiracy belief, suggesting a shared cognitive underpinning ([Mehl et al., 2020](https://www.psypost.org/2020/12/psychology-study-uncovers-new-details-about-the-cognitive-underpinnings-of-belief-in-conspiracy-theories-58772)).

Another relevant bias is **hypersensitive agency detection**, where individuals over-attribute events to intentional agents or hidden forces. This teleologic thinking leads to the assumption that significant events must have purposeful causes, often conspiratorial in nature ([Psychology Today, 2019](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/psych-unseen/201904/what-makes-people-believe-in-conspiracy-theories)).

### 1.3 Analytical Thinking and Education

Lower levels of **analytic thinking** and education are associated with greater susceptibility to conspiracy beliefs. Individuals who engage less in critical evaluation of information are more prone to accept conspiratorial explanations ([Psychology Today, 2019](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/psych-unseen/201904/what-makes-people-believe-in-conspiracy-theories)).

