## 2. Personality Traits and Psychological Profiles

### 2.1 Pathological Antecedents: Paranoia and Schizotypy

A significant body of research links conspiracy beliefs to **psychopathological traits**, particularly **paranoia** and **schizotypy**. Paranoid ideation involves suspiciousness and the belief that others intend harm, which aligns closely with conspiratorial thinking. Schizotypy encompasses traits such as magical thinking and unusual beliefs, further predisposing individuals to conspiracy theories ([Goreis & Voracek, 2019](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full); [Darwin et al., 2011](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0191886911001036)).

### 2.2 Non-Pathological Personality Traits

Research also explores associations between conspiracy beliefs and the **Big Five personality traits**:

| Trait           | Association with Conspiracy Beliefs                  | Notes                                                                                  |
|-----------------|-----------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Agreeableness   | Negative (disagreeableness linked to suspicion)     | Lower agreeableness correlates with antagonism and suspicion, fostering conspiracy belief ([Swami et al., 2010](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full)) |
| Openness        | Mixed/unclear                                       | High openness may relate to seeking novel ideas, but meta-analyses find no consistent effect ([Goreis & Voracek, 2019](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full)) |
| Neuroticism     | Positive                                            | Linked to anxiety and uncertainty, which can increase conspiracy belief ([Hollander, 2017](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full)) |
| Conscientiousness | No significant association                         | Meta-analyses show no clear link ([Goreis & Voracek, 2019](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full)) |
| Extraversion    | No significant association                          |                                                                                         |

Other traits such as **narcissism**, **self-esteem**, **impulsivity**, **anxiety**, and **depression** have been found to have small but significant positive correlations with conspiracy belief ([Bowes et al., 2020](https://www.insider.com/people-believe-conspiracy-theories-if-they-are-detached-narcissistic-2020-10); [Cichocka et al., 2016](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2019.00205/full)).

